# make a function
simple.reg<-function(variable){
  lm.fit<-lm(Mobility~variable)
  print(knitr::kable(summary(lm.fit)$coef, caption='Coefficients'))
  ggplot(dat, mapping=aes(variable, Mobility)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm')
}

b. Use a resampling method to obtain 95% confidence interval. Can you build a 95% prediction interval?

boot <- list()
for(i in 1:500){
  boot[[i]] <- final.dat.5 %>% sample_n(size=100) %>% select(Mobility,Middle_class) %>%
    summarise(realy=mean(Mobility,na.rm=T), x=mean(Middle_class,na.rm=T))
}
boot_df <- bind_rows(boot)
realy <- boot_df[,1]
x <- boot_df[,2]
yhat <- predict(lm.fit.10a, newdata=data.frame(Middle_class=x))
# confidence interval
conf.lm<-as_tibble(predict(lm.fit.10a, newdata=data.frame(Middle_class=x), interval="confidence"))
plot(realy, yhat, type="n", pch=22, xlab="Actual Mobility",
     ylab="Predicted Mobility", main="10b confidence interval", 
     ylim=c(min(conf.lm$lwr), max(conf.lm$upr)))
segments(realy, conf.lm$lwr, realy, conf.lm$upr, col="grey")
abline(a=0, b=1, lty="dashed")
points(realy, conf.lm$fit, pch=16, cex=0.1)

# prediction interval
preds.lm<-as_tibble(predict(lm.fit.10a, newdata=data.frame(Middle_class=x), interval="predict"))
plot(realy, yhat, type="n", pch=22, xlab="Actual Mobility",
     ylab="Predicted Mobility", main="10b prediction interval", 
     ylim=c(0, max(preds.lm$upr)))
segments(realy, preds.lm$lwr, realy, preds.lm$upr, col="grey")
abline(a=0, b=1, lty="dashed")
points(realy, preds.lm$fit, pch=16, cex=0.1)
